    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_3390_metabo11030163__task_003/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The system we devised uses an extra layer of tags inserted into an existing data spreadsheet at specific locations that tell the extract command how to transform the data sections of the sheet (i.e., data tables) into key-based records representable in both JSON format and a relational database... The heart of the extract module is a tag parser that identifies pound-delimited tags which direct the extraction of data from tabular files as tags and associated data are parsed.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes tag parser converting tagged tabular data to JSON, but the specific tag syntax shown in the card (#<table_name>.id and #.<field_name>) is not explicitly documented in passages. Paper mentions 'pound-delimited tags' and describes tagging system with 'export', 'automation', and 'modification' parts, but exact tag format syntax is not detailed in provided passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-3390-metabo13070842",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_003",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "How does the parser convert a tagged tabular file (using export tags like #<table_name>.id and #.<field_name>) into the nested JSON structure required by the directive resolvers?",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T14:07:18.965318+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/10_3390_metabo11030163__task_003/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Once extracted, the data is organized into a JSON representation... The data schema developed for MESSES was designed to capture generalized experimental descriptions and data in an abstract way... It is organized into several tables with a unique record identifier and a flexible collection of fields... There are 6 tables: project, study, protocol, entity, measurement, and factor.",
